CSS provides a few properties that can be used to detect the start and end of a scroll event. These properties are `scroll-behavior`, `scroll-snap-type`, and `scroll-snap-align`.

The `scroll-behavior` property controls the scrolling behavior of an element. By setting it to `smooth`, the browser will use a smooth scrolling animation when the user scrolls the element. You can use the `scroll-behavior` property to detect the start of a scroll event, as the browser will start the smooth scrolling animation when the user scrolls the element.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to use the `scroll-behavior` property to detect the start of a scroll event:

```
